Step 1: Create a README File
On your local computer, create a file named README.md (or README.txt if you donâ€™t want Markdown formatting).
Add content to your README file. For example:

 # My Static Website
This is a simple static website hosted locally using Apache/Nginx.

## Features
- Hosted locally.
- Basic HTML structure.

## Usage
Open the browser and navigate to `http://localhost`.

## Author
Your Name

Step 2: Initialize a Git Repository (if not done already)
Open a terminal in the directory where your website files (e.g., index.html) are stored.
Run the following commands:
 git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"

Step 3: Create a GitHub Repository
Log in to your GitHub account.
Click the + icon (top-right corner) and select New Repository.
Fill in the repository name (e.g., static-website) and click Create repository.
Step 4: Link the Local Repository to GitHub
Copy the remote URL of your GitHub repository (e.g., https://github.com/username/static-website.git).
Add the remote URL to your local repository:

git remote add origin https://github.com/username/static-website.git

git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

Step 5: Verify the README on GitHub
Go to your GitHub repository page.
You should see the README.md content displayed on the repository's main page.
